ligate Israel to observe the Divine Law. While this turn towards legalism is pan-tannaitic, two distinct legal arguments can be identified in tannaitic literature. These specific arguments about the Divine Law’s authority, link to a set of issues regarding the tannaim’s conception of Divine Law and of Israel’s election.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 26. Apr 2024) 7aRELIGION / Judaism / Sacred Writings.2bisacsh  aAntiquity.  aDivine Law.  aElection of Israel.  aIsrael.  aJewish law.  aJewish philosophy.  aLegalism.  aMidrash Halakha.  aMidrash.  aRabbinics.  aTannaitic Midrash.  atannaim.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertAcademic Studies Press Complete eBook-Package 2024z978311143260108iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertDG Plus PP Package 2024 Part 2z978311133238340uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/979888719413440uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9798887194134423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9798887194134/original  a978-3-11-133238-3  DG Plus PP Package 2024 Part 2b2024  a978-3-11-143260-1  Academic Studies Press Complete eBook-Package 2024b2024  aEBA_CL_PLTLJSIS  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_PLTLJSIS  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles